<paragraph id="341836CCB565DB786CD7B578FEBCF974" blockId="7.[151,532,1768,1829]" box="[151,379,1804,1829]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">
(
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB786CDFB578FEE7F975" box="[159,288,1804,1829]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1766,1789]" captionTargetBox="[232,1349,195,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[232,1350,195,1734]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in dorsal and ventral views. 1 – 2 M. gracielae sp. nov., male holotype. 3 – 4 M. monostigma monostigma, male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil. 5 – 8 M. nepticula stigmosa, 5 – 6 male; 7 – 8 female. 9 – 12 M. eupteryx stat. rest., 9 – 10 male from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 11 – 12 female. 13 – 14 M. nola, male from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil. 15 – 20 M. paraena, 15 – 16 male from Cáceres, Mato Grosso, Brazil; 17 – 18 male; 19 – 20 female. 21 – 28 M. epaphus (23 – 28 upper side left, underside right), 21 – 22 M. epaphus pyrrha, male; 23 female from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil; 24 female from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 25 M. epaphus epaphus, male from Belém, Pará, Brazil; 26 M. epaphus pyrrha, male from São Paulo de Olivença, Amazonas, Brazil; 27 – 28, M. epaphus pyrrha, males from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil. 29 – 32 M. leucophrys, 29 – 30 male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil; 31 – 32 female. Scale bar 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256291/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Figs 29–32</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB786D6BB578FE8DF975" box="[299,330,1804,1828]" captionStart="FIGURES 33 – 40" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1900,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,193,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1880]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 33 – 40. Male genitalia of Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in lateral view. 33 M. gracielae sp. nov., holotype. 34 M. monostigma monostigma. 35 M. nepticula stigmosa. 36 M. eupteryx stat. rest. from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil (DZ 36.494). 37 M. nola from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil (DZ 36.794). 38 M. paraena. 39 M. epaphus pyrrha. 40 M. leucophrys. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/161477/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB786D15B578FEB5F974" box="[341,370,1804,1829]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 45" captionStartId="6.[151,264,913,936]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,891]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,892]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 45. Female genitalia of Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in ventral view. 41, M. nepticula stigmosa. 42, M. eupteryx stat. rest. 43, M. paraena. 44, M. epaphus pyrrha from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil (DZ 36.504). 45, M. leucophrys. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/161478/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">45</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7CBD6547B565DB786CD7B520FE74F9E4" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" type="description">
<paragraph id="341836CCB565DB786CD7B520FE74F9E4" blockId="7.[151,1436,1876,2009]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">
Three males and one female were captured in PNSD, one male in 2011 and the remainder in 2014. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB78693DB521FED5F9C1" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucophrys">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB78693DB521FED5F9C1" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. leucophrys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were observed on the hilltop flying slowly about one to two meters from the ground during the end of the day (around 17:00h.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7CBD6547B565DB776C87B5B5FE1DFF4C" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="471" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="341836CCB565DB776C87B5B5FE1DFF4C" blockId="7.[151,1436,1876,2009]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="471" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786C87B5B5FE66F988" box="[199,417,1984,2009]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucophrys">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786C87B5B5FE66F988" box="[199,417,1984,2009]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Mesene leucophrys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the species with the most extensive synonymic list of the genus (
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB565DB776949B5B4FEE1FEE1" author="Callaghan" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="471" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" refString="Callaghan, C. J. &amp; Lamas, G. (2004) Riodinidae. In: Lamas, G. (Ed.), Checklist: Part 4 A. Hesperioidea-Papilionoidea. In: Heppner, J. B. (Ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera 5 A. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera / Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, pp. 141 - 170." type="book chapter" year="2004">Callaghan &amp; Lamas 2004</bibRefCitation>
), with nine synonyms, which serves as an indication of its variable phenotype. The specimens from 
<collectionCode id="52B6AE09B56ADB776CD7B2C8FF18FE85" box="[151,223,188,212]" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">PNSD</collectionCode>
have a phenotype similar to that of the 
<typeStatus id="EB1C886EB56ADB776EE9B2C9FD1EFE84" box="[681,729,189,213]" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB56ADB776F34B2C9FBD0FE84" box="[884,1047,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucophrys">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB56ADB776F34B2C9FBD0FE84" box="[884,1047,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">M. leucophrys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB56ADB77693DB2C9FE18FEA9" authority="Warren et al. 2016" authorityName="Warren et al." authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paraena">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB56ADB77693DB2C9FF33FEA9" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">M. paraena</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB56ADB776D42B294FE10FEA9" author="Warren" box="[258,471,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="471" refString="Warren, A. D., Davis, K. J., Stangeland, E. M., Pelham, J. P. &amp; Grishin, N. V. (2016) Illustrated lists of American butterflies (North and South America). Available from: http: // butterfliesofamerica. com / L / Neotropical. htm (accessed 23 May 2016)" type="journal article" year="2016">
Warren 
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB56ADB776D1CB295FE53FEA9" box="[348,404,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Due to distribution of 
<collectionCode id="52B6AE09B56ADB776E9FB294FCD2FEA9" box="[735,789,224,248]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15690" name="California Academy of Sciences" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">CAS</collectionCode>
and morphology of male genitalia, this species belongs to the “ 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB56ADB776C8CB370FEE2FF4C" box="[204,293,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phareus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB56ADB776C8CB370FEE2FF4C" box="[204,293,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="471">phareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” species group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
